190 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PHILIPPINE COUP ATTEMPT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Let's see if I have this right now. The Bush Administration says that its 
military support of the Philippine government to suppress the rebellion was 
legal because international law permits governments under attack to seek 
outside help. But the Nicaraguan government, under attack for eight years, was 
not allowed to seek help from the Soviets or anyone else. 
</P>
<P>
And the United States is allowed to take sides in the El Salvador civil war, 
but no one else is allowed to support the other side. 
</P>
<P>
And the Soviet Union should not interfere in the Western Hemisphere, but the 
United States can support the rebels in Afghanistan. 
</P>
<P>
And the government and society of Iran are highly repressive, but the Afghan 
rebels, who will institute a very similar system if they take power, are 
freedom fighters. 
</P>
<P>
And it's a marvelous thing that the Soviet Union has allowed Eastern Europe to 
freely pursue its own path, but the U.S. should not do the same for Central 
America. 
</P>
<P>
And union militancy, a multiparty electoral system and social reform are 
wonderful to see in Eastern Europe, but they have no place in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
WILLIAM BLUM 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
