<HEADLINE>
<P>
SHOUP SAYS CLU'S DECISION NOT FINAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BRENDAN HEALEY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cal Lutheran may say he is fired but, according to Coach Bob Shoup, the last 
shot has not been heard. 
</P>
<P>
"There are some processes that are appropriate to faculty, and that's where I 
am right now," Shoup said Monday evening after returning from San Jose. 
</P>
<P>
The university issued an announcement Friday saying Shoup had been released, 
but he contends that the situation is still being resolved. 
</P>
<P>
"A number of people met today on this issue, and I need to be updated," Shoup 
said. "It's out of the (Board of) Regents (hands), and there is a process and 
it's just starting." 
</P>
<P>
Shoup declined to name the parties involved in what he says are ongoing 
discussions, but when asked if he considered his release a finality, Shoup 
said: "I'm not sure I should answer that for fear it would be looked on as a 
challenge to the administration." 
</P>
<P>
Shoup also refused to reply to published comments by University President Jerry 
Miller. 
</P>
<P>
"I know Miller took some shots, and I'm not sure exactly why," Shoup said. 
BRENDAN HEALEY 
</P>
</TEXT>
