<HEADLINE>
<P>
SRI LANKAN BUDDHISTS UNVEIL STUFFED ELEPHANT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
KANDY, Sri Lanka 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Buddhists today unveiled a stuffed version of Raja, a sacred elephant whose 
death in 1988 plunged Sri Lanka into mourning. The grand old elephant, who 
after $4,000 worth of taxidermy work looked more robust than in his last years 
of life, stood majestically inside the Budhhist temple with two strings of 
white flowers hanging from his tusks. 
</P>
