<P>
STALIN AIDE CHARGES DROPPED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NORRISTOWN, Pa. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Prosecutors dropped assault and harassment charges against a man who once 
served as the bodyguard of Soviet leader Josef Stalin. 
</P>
<P>
Alexander Comfort had been charged by Plymouth Township police with pushing a 
social worker down on his bed and sexually assaulting her when she went to his 
home to offer counseling after his wife's death. 
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors Monday said the woman was no longer interested in pursuing the 
matter. 
</P>
<P>
Comfort, 67, served as a member of the Russian Secret Police from 1939 to 1942. 
He allegedly attacked the woman after showing her pictures of him posing with 
Stalin and Nikita S. Khrushchev. 
</P>
</TEXT>
