<P>
KUROSAWA TO GET HONORARY OSCAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Service Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Akira Kurosawa, 79-year-old Japanese director of such films as "Rashomon" and 
"Seven Samurai," will receive an honorary Oscar award at the presentations 
March 26, the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
"The award will be presented to Kurosawa for his cinematic accomplishments that 
have inspired, delighted, enriched and entertained worldwide audiences and 
influenced filmmakers throughout the world," the academy, which presents the 
awards, said. 
</P>
<P>
Kurosawa, whose 1951 production of "Rashomon" won an Oscar for best foreign 
language film, is also a film producer and scriptwriter. 
</P>
<P>
His 1975 film "Dersu Uzala," submitted by the Soviet Union, also won an Oscar 
for best foreign language film, making him the only director to win that 
category for two countries. He was nominated as best director in 1985 for 
"Ran." 
