<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
HOCKEY HALL OF FAME ON THIN ICE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
EVELETH, Minn. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The U.S. Hockey Hall of Fame may have to close temporarily because of financial 
problems, according to its board Chairman John Heneman. 
</P>
<P>
"We are in deep financial trouble," Heneman said Monday. "We just don't have 
any money and it may be that it may have to be closed temporarily. We get lots 
of promises, but we haven't got any money." 
</P>
<P>
The board has considered private and public sources for operating money, 
Heneman said. Hall of Fame board members met last summer with Gov. Rudy Perpich 
and were encouraged, but so far no state money has been made available, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
A total of 72 U.S.-born hockey standouts have been named to the hall, which 
opened in 1973. 
</P>
</TEXT>
