<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: WEEKEND BOX OFFICE; 
</P>
<P>
'ROSES' BURNS 'SHE-DEVIL' IN OPENING BOUT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DANIEL CERONE , Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Michael Douglas and Kathleen Turner shoved aside Meryl Streep and Roseanne Barr 
in the box office, as Fox's black comedy "The War of the Roses" opened with 
$9.7 million, compared to $3.5 million for the debut of Orion's "She-Devil." 
Both films feature big-name celebrities in marital battles, but in per-screen 
averages, the final count was: Douglas-Turner $7,696, Streep-Barr $2,502. 
Warner Bros.' holiday spoof "National Lampoon's Christmas Vacation" finished a 
close second to "War of the Roses" with $9.5 million. Universal's "Back to the 
Future Part II" continued to plunge since its record-breaking Thanksgiving 
opening, falling 42% in the box office over its third weekend. 
</P>
<P>
* Transworld's "Triumph of the Spirit," a dramatic look at Auschwitz through 
the eyes of an interred Jewish boxer, opened with $26,167 on two screens in Los 
Angeles and New York. 
</P>
